WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.664 --> 00:00:06.580
SPEAKER: Hi, everyone.

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:08.460
Thank you so much
for being here.

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:12.420
On behalf of [? Hola ?] LAX,
Google Talks At, and Latino

00:00:12.420 --> 00:00:14.419
Heritage LA, I'd like
to welcome everyone

00:00:14.419 --> 00:00:16.710
to our first Hispanic Heritage
Month event, where we're

00:00:16.710 --> 00:00:19.410
going to have a panel
discussion, where we celebrate

00:00:19.410 --> 00:00:22.440
the vibrancy of Latinidad or
the many different aspects that

00:00:22.440 --> 00:00:23.850
make us Latino.

00:00:23.850 --> 00:00:26.550
Today, we will hear firsthand
from three very talented

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:28.922
local Latina artists,
each one of them

00:00:28.922 --> 00:00:30.630
providing their own
take on what it means

00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:32.560
to be an artist in the US.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:35.070
I will start with
Sandra in the middle.

00:00:35.070 --> 00:00:37.350
Sandra Cornejo is a
first-generation Salvadoran

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:40.050
American artist born
in Houston, Texas.

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:42.210
Historical collective
memory of post-civil war

00:00:42.210 --> 00:00:44.730
Salvadoran culture is
an important influence

00:00:44.730 --> 00:00:46.530
and inspiration for her work.

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:49.200
She recently implemented a
portfolio preparation course

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:51.600
at Plaza de la Raza
for students aspiring

00:00:51.600 --> 00:00:54.600
to continue their education
and profession in the arts.

00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:57.900
Sandra received a BFA from
VCU, with a concentration

00:00:57.900 --> 00:00:59.550
in painting and printmaking.

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:02.160
Recipient of the Ellen
Battell Stoeckel Fellowship,

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:04.980
she attended the Yale
Norfolk Summer Program.

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:05.898
Thanks for being here.

00:01:05.898 --> 00:01:06.981
SANDRA CORNEJO: Thank you.

00:01:06.981 --> 00:01:07.760
Thanks for having me.

00:01:07.760 --> 00:01:10.010
SPEAKER: Then we have Yolanda
all the way to the left,

00:01:10.010 --> 00:01:12.870
or to your right, was born
into a family whose artistic

00:01:12.870 --> 00:01:15.720
heritage dates back to 1877.

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:18.570
Gonzalez's travels in different
countries, the bonds forged

00:01:18.570 --> 00:01:20.280
with individuals
in those places,

00:01:20.280 --> 00:01:22.680
and the resulting
transformative experiences

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:25.290
are reflected in her
art and her life.

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:27.290
She is known for her
strong, bold brush

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:29.970
strokes of color and
texture, intent on evoking

00:01:29.970 --> 00:01:31.800
imagination and emotion.

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:34.320
She was an artist in
residence in Ginza, Japan,

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:37.167
followed by a similar
stint in Assisi, Italy.

00:01:37.167 --> 00:01:39.750
Throughout the years, Gonzalez
has taught at various community

00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:40.740
organizations.

00:01:40.740 --> 00:01:43.110
You can see some of her
work on the gold line trains

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:47.590
as well as buses throughout LA
in a collaboration with AARP.

00:01:47.590 --> 00:01:50.232
Yolanda studied at the Pasadena
Art Center College of Design

00:01:50.232 --> 00:01:52.440
after winning a painting
competition that awarded her

00:01:52.440 --> 00:01:54.630
a scholarship to the
prestigious school.

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:55.180
Thanks again.

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:55.890
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
Thanks for having me.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:57.000
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.300
And now we have Rosalie Lopez,
a Los Angeles-based artist

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:02.700
whose work involves combining
cultural iconography

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:05.190
with references of her
everyday surroundings.

00:02:05.190 --> 00:02:07.320
At a young age, she
was heavily impacted

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.600
with the realities of loss,
addictions, and violence

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:11.310
within her immediate
family, which

00:02:11.310 --> 00:02:13.230
continue to shape her
perspectives in society

00:02:13.230 --> 00:02:14.310
and culture.

00:02:14.310 --> 00:02:17.820
She primarily uses printmaking,
papel picado, installation,

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:19.950
and the altar offering
to relay experiences

00:02:19.950 --> 00:02:22.090
of survival, loss, and pride.

00:02:22.090 --> 00:02:23.820
Rosalie earned a
master of fine arts

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:26.700
in printmaking from Indiana
University and dual bachelor

00:02:26.700 --> 00:02:28.440
of fine arts degrees
in graphic design

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.980
and printmaking from California
State University, Long Beach.

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:33.570
All three women have
had their artwork

00:02:33.570 --> 00:02:35.790
exhibited in many museums
around the country

00:02:35.790 --> 00:02:36.760
and internationally.

00:02:36.760 --> 00:02:38.882
So let's give them
a warm welcome.

00:02:38.882 --> 00:02:40.325
[APPLAUSE]

