00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:51.160
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: They do.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:51.810
They have some.

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:53.791
They have a house in Tulum.

00:04:53.791 --> 00:04:55.540
And they've taken some
portraits that I've

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:56.790
created of them to their home.

00:04:56.790 --> 00:04:58.190
SPEAKER: That's wonderful.

00:04:58.190 --> 00:04:58.690
Thank you.

00:04:58.690 --> 00:04:59.890
Thank you so much.

00:04:59.890 --> 00:05:04.190
And then on the next page,
we have Rosalie's work.

00:05:04.190 --> 00:05:06.400
Rosalie, you have four
different pieces here

00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:08.290
with papel picado
and different things.

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:10.925
Tell us, why these
specific pieces?

00:05:10.925 --> 00:05:13.300
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Kind of going
off what Yolanda was saying,

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:15.460
I wanted to pick
work that exemplified

00:05:15.460 --> 00:05:17.950
what I'm creating right now.

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:20.640
As a printmaker and
someone who combines

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:22.390
that with papel picado,
I wanted to choose

00:05:22.390 --> 00:05:26.560
works that talk about
the ofrenda and offering

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:32.050
in a very contemporary way, in
untraditional somewhat ways.

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:36.580
So I have a papel picado
piece of an LA scene, a family

00:05:36.580 --> 00:05:40.690
portrait that I combine
with LED lights and a couple

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:45.100
other ofrenda pieces that
are all papel picado.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:47.080
So I felt like
together, they make

00:05:47.080 --> 00:05:50.620
a grouping that really talks
about the things that I feel

00:05:50.620 --> 00:05:52.704
embody the concepts
that I work with.

00:05:52.704 --> 00:05:53.620
SPEAKER: That's great.

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:54.510
Thank you.

00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:56.380
Yeah.

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.280
So you do these and
also tons of other?

00:05:58.280 --> 00:05:59.155
Because you combine--

00:05:59.155 --> 00:06:01.240
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I do
installation art.

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:04.630
Sometimes, it's just pure
printmaking mixed together

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:06.040
sometimes with papel picado.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.100
So I really enjoy creating--

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:11.500
transforming spaces to
give people an experience.

00:06:11.500 --> 00:06:14.380
So sometimes, that means
breaking out of the frame

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:16.290
and inhabiting a space.

00:06:16.290 --> 00:06:17.601
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:06:17.601 --> 00:06:18.100
Thank you.

00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:19.232
That's great.

00:06:19.232 --> 00:06:20.940
And now we're going
to see Sandra's work.

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:22.480
And Sandra's very specific.

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:24.874
You have this big, huge artwork.

00:06:24.874 --> 00:06:26.290
SANDRA CORNEJO: I
chose one piece.

00:06:26.290 --> 00:06:26.831
SPEAKER: One.

00:06:26.831 --> 00:06:28.567
I'm very curious, why one?

00:06:28.567 --> 00:06:29.650
SANDRA CORNEJO: One piece.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:33.670
Well, it's a group of work
that I'm currently working on.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:36.490
I tend to work in series.

00:06:36.490 --> 00:06:41.890
So at the moment, I'm exploring
notions of childhood, memory,

00:06:41.890 --> 00:06:46.280
nostalgia, like what drives
that nostalgic power.

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:48.145
And this image is--

00:06:48.145 --> 00:06:50.380
is it something that's
been romanticized?

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:52.210
Something that's been skewed?

00:06:52.210 --> 00:06:54.624
Like why?

00:06:54.624 --> 00:06:55.790
Why does it have that power?

00:06:55.790 --> 00:06:59.050
So I love kind of
asking these questions

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:00.440
as I'm making the work.

00:07:00.440 --> 00:07:03.910
So as you see this piece,
it's representational,

00:07:03.910 --> 00:07:06.590
yet has very abstract
elements to it.

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:11.350
So kind of like a push and pull,
like an inquiry of my past,

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:13.240
like where I come from.

00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:16.420
So it's a very
tender, loving memory.

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:20.590
It's a bit like discombobulated
and may make sense.

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:25.080
And it might bring truth to
some of my viewers, I hope.

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:26.320
SPEAKER: No, I loved it.

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:27.464
All the work is beautiful.

00:07:27.464 --> 00:07:28.880
And I thought it
was very powerful

00:07:28.880 --> 00:07:30.490
that you just chose one.

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:31.480
SANDRA CORNEJO: Yeah.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:32.688
SPEAKER: I need to know more.

00:07:32.688 --> 00:07:36.910
[LAUGHS] So I like
to know also--

00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:39.400
so you were talking about
themes and how right now,

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.802
you're working on this
theme of childhood.

00:07:41.802 --> 00:07:42.720
What drives a theme?

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:44.580
Like For all three
of you, when you

00:07:44.580 --> 00:07:47.670
work on a theme, what is
that driver or that influence

00:07:47.670 --> 00:07:49.620
to go on that theme?

00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:51.455
How do you choose the
theme that is next?

00:07:51.455 --> 00:07:52.830
SANDRA CORNEJO:
Well, there tends

00:07:52.830 --> 00:07:55.800
to be themes that I've been
working with for a really

00:07:55.800 --> 00:07:58.950
long time, whether
it's commemorating

00:07:58.950 --> 00:08:01.290
a figure, like in
a monolithic space,

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:02.670
like one figure in a space.

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:03.390
Like why?

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:05.040
Like telling a story.

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:07.470
Always very narrative-like.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:11.340
So childhood, social
justice, where I'm from--

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:12.210
El Salvador.

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:13.540
Like, it's history.

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:16.480
So it's very historically-based.

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:18.960
And I'm always seeking
out a narrative.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.360
And whatever that
narrative may be,

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:25.080
that's the image that surfaces.

00:08:25.080 --> 00:08:26.360
SPEAKER: Great.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:28.619
How does it work
for both of you?

00:08:28.619 --> 00:08:30.160
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
I think for myself,

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:32.200
it's something
that's very personal.

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:36.120
And I try to cover
narratives that

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:41.549
are what people are going
through along with myself.

00:08:41.549 --> 00:08:46.170
And that reality and how that
reality is portrayed on canvas

00:08:46.170 --> 00:08:49.505
in a beautiful manner.

00:08:49.505 --> 00:08:50.460
SPEAKER: Thank you.

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:51.835
ROSALIE LOPEZ: In
my case, I feel

00:08:51.835 --> 00:08:57.030
like I'm very much inspired by
my community, my neighborhood.

00:08:57.030 --> 00:08:59.280
And in the beginning,
a lot of my work

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:02.040
was definitely influenced
by Dia de los Muertos altars

00:09:02.040 --> 00:09:05.370
and how women would use
these altars as a platform

00:09:05.370 --> 00:09:07.620
to discuss social
issues in the community

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:11.160
as a way to have a voice and
gathering assemblage work.

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:15.855
And so from that, and
using my own experiences,

00:09:15.855 --> 00:09:21.750
I use it as a way to talk about
people who I want to praise

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:25.590
or I want to commemorate
and how we can take pride

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:27.870
in our communal
histories and stories

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:30.400
and display them as something
to be very proud about.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:31.080
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:32.640
Do you feel that--

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:36.600
so of course, artwork
is your emotion.

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:38.450
There's a voice behind it.

00:09:38.450 --> 00:09:42.000
Do you feel there's a voice or
an emotion that you tap into,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.620
and when you do,
better work comes out?

00:09:44.620 --> 00:09:45.130
What it is?

00:09:45.130 --> 00:09:47.671
Some people are like, I need
to be depressed or [INAUDIBLE]..

00:09:47.671 --> 00:09:49.020
I don't know.

00:09:49.020 --> 00:09:51.270
I'm not an artist like
this, to this magnitude.

00:09:51.270 --> 00:09:54.620
I do little things for
my children, but not--

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:57.180
or certainly like in school.

00:09:57.180 --> 00:09:59.400
Tell me, how does that work
for you in that process?

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:02.460
SANDRA CORNEJO: No,
definitely, like for me

00:10:02.460 --> 00:10:04.540
in my works, the struggle.

00:10:04.540 --> 00:10:11.700
Like, a struggle, any struggle,
perseverance, overcoming,

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:16.080
beauty, like all of these
very strong elements

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:19.850
that just run through all of
my work is what drives it.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:24.080
Like, absolutely.

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:28.910
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I definitely feel
like in my case, the materials

00:10:28.910 --> 00:10:33.050
that I use and the person
that I'm dedicating it to

00:10:33.050 --> 00:10:34.280
are things that I harness.

00:10:34.280 --> 00:10:37.310
And I want that energy
to transmute and infuse

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:39.050
into the artwork.

00:10:39.050 --> 00:10:41.300
So I pull on a lot
of those emotions.

00:10:41.300 --> 00:10:43.190
Most of the people I
use are people that I'm

00:10:43.190 --> 00:10:44.231
connected to in some way.

00:10:44.231 --> 00:10:46.190
So I have a
relationship with them.

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:49.310
And if I'm commemorating
a past memory

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:53.000
or igniting thoughts
from other viewers in it,

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.490
I want them to
cherish those things

00:10:55.490 --> 00:10:59.677
and to have value so
that they don't forget.

00:10:59.677 --> 00:11:00.260
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:00.920
OK.

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:02.586
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I
think my inspiration

00:11:02.586 --> 00:11:04.850
is people, the
relationships that we have,

00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:09.145
and the emotions that they evoke
in my soul and in my heart.

00:11:09.145 --> 00:11:10.520
So when there's
somebody that I'm

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:13.430
passionate about that I'm
creating a portrait of,

00:11:13.430 --> 00:11:15.249
you definitely see
it on the canvas.

00:11:15.249 --> 00:11:16.040
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:11:16.040 --> 00:11:17.248
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Absolutely.

00:11:17.248 --> 00:11:18.427
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:11:18.427 --> 00:11:20.510
So it's that emotion that
we're discussing, right?

00:11:20.510 --> 00:11:20.860
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Yes.

00:11:20.860 --> 00:11:22.210
SPEAKER: So when
you're doing people--

00:11:22.210 --> 00:11:24.335
I mean, it's people you're
passionate about or very

00:11:24.335 --> 00:11:26.194
excited to evoke.

00:11:26.194 --> 00:11:27.860
Is it just all pure
happiness, or do you

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:30.584
have like inner emotions
that are coming out

00:11:30.584 --> 00:11:32.500
in this painting, too,
that you're trying to--

00:11:32.500 --> 00:11:34.517
I mean, like there's
always subliminal messages.

00:11:34.517 --> 00:11:35.350
Do you do that, too?

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:36.725
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
I think there's

00:11:36.725 --> 00:11:38.690
all kinds of emotions
that transpire

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:40.190
in the creative process.

00:11:40.190 --> 00:11:44.060
And it's that relationship
between your canvas.

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:46.100
And since I've been
painting for 30 years,

00:11:46.100 --> 00:11:47.677
it's a love relationship.

00:11:47.677 --> 00:11:48.260
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:51.510
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: And it's
this medium that feeds my soul.

00:11:51.510 --> 00:11:54.330
And then, there's
this other person.

00:11:54.330 --> 00:11:57.230
So it's a dialogue
between the three of us.

00:11:57.230 --> 00:12:00.230
Between the creative
process the canvas, myself,

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:03.440
and the sitter, the
portrait I'm creating of.

00:12:03.440 --> 00:12:06.380
And so definitely,
there's different emotions

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:07.060
that come out.

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:11.300
And it's lovely to
allow yourself to convey

00:12:11.300 --> 00:12:12.757
that with the brushstrokes.

00:12:12.757 --> 00:12:13.340
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:12:13.340 --> 00:12:14.548
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Definitely.

00:12:14.548 --> 00:12:15.050
Yeah.

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:15.758
SPEAKER: Tell me.

00:12:15.758 --> 00:12:16.410
Tell me.

00:12:16.410 --> 00:12:17.000
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I was
just going to say,

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.755
it's like a form
of communicating.

00:12:18.755 --> 00:12:20.750
Instead of using words,
you can say it best

00:12:20.750 --> 00:12:23.120
with images and textures.

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.586
And as those things layer,
it creates the emotion

00:12:25.586 --> 00:12:26.960
that you're not
quite able to put

00:12:26.960 --> 00:12:29.380
into the same sort of wording.

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:30.529
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:12:30.529 --> 00:12:32.570
ROSALIE LOPEZ: You hope
that people get that when

00:12:32.570 --> 00:12:34.880
they see it, or it allows
them to see something

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:36.830
in a different
way, because that's

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:39.170
how you find your mode of
communication happening best.

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:40.067
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:12:40.067 --> 00:12:42.650
So it's like for the next Google
Talk, we'll just have easels.

00:12:42.650 --> 00:12:43.962
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:43.962 --> 00:12:45.170
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Absolutely.

00:12:45.170 --> 00:12:47.010
Great idea.

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:48.610
Let's do it.

00:12:48.610 --> 00:12:51.821
SPEAKER: So I'm very proud to
