there's a lot of men in it, too.

00:13:07.550 --> 00:13:08.120
Tell me.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:10.370
I want to know.

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:12.170
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
There are obstacles.

00:13:12.170 --> 00:13:13.820
I tend to not focus on them.

00:13:13.820 --> 00:13:17.840
I just continue to forge
forward and to continue

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:20.900
to be focused on what I'm doing
in business and my creativity.

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.517
So there's Yolanda Gonzalez,
who is the artist, the creative.

00:13:24.517 --> 00:13:26.600
And there is Yolanda
Gonzalez, the businessperson.

00:13:26.600 --> 00:13:29.430
And that was taught to me by
my dad, Leopoldo Gonzalez,

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:31.910
who was a great businessman.

00:13:31.910 --> 00:13:36.380
So I think if you can separate
yourself from the creative,

00:13:36.380 --> 00:13:40.899
and then to the business
of this beautiful painting

00:13:40.899 --> 00:13:43.190
that you're going to hand
over, that your soul is going

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:44.690
to hang in somebody's home.

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:46.920
I think it's important
to focus on that.

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:49.220
So there are
obstacles, but I think

00:13:49.220 --> 00:13:55.910
like in any other line
of work, I just focus on

00:13:55.910 --> 00:13:58.980
a clear, straight,
and narrow road.

00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:01.424
And that's to my goal.

00:14:01.424 --> 00:14:03.090
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It's
the Latino backbone.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.450
We have parents and family
who teach us how to work hard,

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:12.080
who show us what it's like to
have dedication into something.

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:15.200
And I feel like I definitely
pull from that, too.

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:17.139
My mom, single parent mom.

00:14:17.139 --> 00:14:18.680
And what she did to
make things work.

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:20.870
And you use that,
transmute that into what

00:14:20.870 --> 00:14:22.830
goals you want to accomplish.

00:14:22.830 --> 00:14:24.477
And it comes through.

00:14:24.477 --> 00:14:26.060
You could tell
people's drive, and you

00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:28.070
could see it
because they learned

00:14:28.070 --> 00:14:29.351
from people before them.

00:14:29.351 --> 00:14:31.350
Not even in the same field
or a different thing,

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:33.176
but they see it being
applied, and then it

00:14:33.176 --> 00:14:35.300
trickles down into your
own personality and the way

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:37.897
that you work.

00:14:37.897 --> 00:14:38.480
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:14:40.252 --> 00:14:42.710
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I think that
there is definitely a struggle.

00:14:42.710 --> 00:14:45.050
Being an artist is not easy.

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:47.540
I wanted Yolanda to
answer first because she's

00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:49.990
got a lot more experience
than Sandra and I.

00:14:49.990 --> 00:14:51.960
We're newer in
this sort of game.

00:14:51.960 --> 00:14:55.730
So I feel like I learned
from women like her

00:14:55.730 --> 00:14:59.480
that their strength
and their passageways,

00:14:59.480 --> 00:15:02.480
them pioneering
these paths for us,

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:05.600
make it a different world for
us than it was, I think, even

00:15:05.600 --> 00:15:06.740
in their timeframe.

00:15:06.740 --> 00:15:08.330
So I acknowledge that.

00:15:08.330 --> 00:15:10.670
I really feel like
they are people

00:15:10.670 --> 00:15:14.100
that I like to look up
to and I learn from.

00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:15.010
I'm a teacher, too.

00:15:15.010 --> 00:15:17.420
So I feel like as an instructor,
as a teacher, sometimes

00:15:17.420 --> 00:15:19.878
the students don't think like,
oh, where is the teacher at?

00:15:19.878 --> 00:15:20.930
Oh, that's me.

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:23.059
I'm right here.

00:15:23.059 --> 00:15:24.850
I appreciate her boldness
and her strength.

00:15:24.850 --> 00:15:26.200
And I think that's
something that I really

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:27.250
admire about Yolanda.

00:15:27.250 --> 00:15:27.760
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Thank you.

00:15:27.760 --> 00:15:29.593
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It comes
through in her work.

00:15:29.593 --> 00:15:34.840
And I feel like I'm
coming to my own in that.

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:37.360
I'm finding that
voice and I'm figuring

00:15:37.360 --> 00:15:39.610
how that communicates
with my surroundings

00:15:39.610 --> 00:15:41.200
and my neighborhood.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:46.780
I feel like I can be a venue
for communicating these things.

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:49.270
How I am impacted
by them and how

00:15:49.270 --> 00:15:51.880
other people see this
happening in our communities.

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:54.340
So we play an important
role in showing people

00:15:54.340 --> 00:15:58.510
that it's not the same route
to understanding what's

00:15:58.510 --> 00:16:01.580
happening in our culture
and our neighborhood.

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:06.070
And I feel thankful to be
a part of events like this

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:10.000
because it's not a voice
that's commonly heard.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.520
It's not a voice where
we often get a platform

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:14.990
to be such a strong voice.

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:17.650
So I appreciate being
involved with it

00:16:17.650 --> 00:16:20.469
and being involved with
artists like these.

00:16:20.469 --> 00:16:21.260
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:21.926
Are you kidding?

00:16:21.926 --> 00:16:22.850
You're always welcome.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:23.940
Yeah.

00:16:23.940 --> 00:16:26.440
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I'd like to
say thank you for saying that.

00:16:26.440 --> 00:16:27.820
I appreciate it.

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:34.390
And I've worked hard to keep
my reputation and my persona

00:16:34.390 --> 00:16:37.440
kind of a certain way for you.

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:39.259
ROSALIE LOPEZ: The
aura comes through.

00:16:39.259 --> 00:16:40.050
SPEAKER: I love it.

