00:18:36.250 --> 00:18:41.442
So teaching art, I feel like
some of my biggest mentors

00:18:41.442 --> 00:18:43.900
that I have, a lot of them were
professors and some of them

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:46.520
were working artists
outside of the institution.

00:18:49.330 --> 00:18:52.000
I try to think about how I can
bring that communal experience

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.582
and working with artists
outside of the institution

00:18:54.582 --> 00:18:57.040
and think about how you can
bring that into the institution

00:18:57.040 --> 00:18:59.020
and work with
students and get them

00:18:59.020 --> 00:19:01.870
to clarify their own voices.

00:19:01.870 --> 00:19:04.480
You're teaching them how to
use a medium and then also, how

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:06.730
to speak through that medium.

00:19:06.730 --> 00:19:09.100
So it's an interesting thing.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:10.600
I think that helps
to pay it back.

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:14.830
I think I'm really happy to
also work at the community level

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:17.200
with places like Plaza
de la Raza, where

00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:21.020
I get to work with youth and
those young kids that just love

00:19:21.020 --> 00:19:22.840
working with art.

00:19:22.840 --> 00:19:24.980
It's not even always
about the end product.

00:19:24.980 --> 00:19:27.022
It's about the process of
working and having fun.

00:19:27.022 --> 00:19:28.771
SANDRA CORNEJO: It's
the experience, yeah.

00:19:28.771 --> 00:19:30.940
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Those
experiences coming together

00:19:30.940 --> 00:19:32.840
are what makes it a lot of fun.

00:19:32.840 --> 00:19:34.025
So yeah.

00:19:34.025 --> 00:19:35.680
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:36.640
Anything over there?

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:37.720
I have more questions.

00:19:37.720 --> 00:19:38.678
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Yeah.

