ROSALIE LOPEZ: I got a story.

00:22:39.240 --> 00:22:40.823
SANDRA CORNEJO: Yeah,
you got a story?

00:22:40.823 --> 00:22:43.234
SPEAKER: I love it.

00:22:43.234 --> 00:22:44.650
ROSALIE LOPEZ:
I've had this idea.

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:47.620
I make a lot of altars
and a lot of offerings.

00:22:47.620 --> 00:22:49.760
So I've had this
idea for a long time.

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:51.880
And I was happy to
be able to do it.

00:22:51.880 --> 00:22:54.080
Finally, like I think
three years into having it,

00:22:54.080 --> 00:22:55.270
it was in my sketchbook.

00:22:55.270 --> 00:22:56.480
I finally get to do it.

00:22:56.480 --> 00:22:59.180
And got grant money to do it.

00:22:59.180 --> 00:23:03.070
But I've always wanted to do
this pop-up altar installation

00:23:03.070 --> 00:23:05.080
dedicated to my mom.

00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:08.350
My mom, when she passed away,
we inherited all of her plants.

00:23:08.350 --> 00:23:11.194
And so my sister and I started
taking care of her plants

00:23:11.194 --> 00:23:13.360
and learning how to have
this green thumb because we

00:23:13.360 --> 00:23:16.630
wanted to preserve her
through these plants.

00:23:16.630 --> 00:23:18.370
And so I've been sprouting them.

00:23:18.370 --> 00:23:20.110
And my sister and I
were living together,

00:23:20.110 --> 00:23:21.610
and then we were
going to part ways.

00:23:21.610 --> 00:23:23.360
She was going to get
a job somewhere else.

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:26.600
And the thought of not having
her plants was like, oh,

00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:27.100
don't worry.

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:28.570
I'm going to clone them.

00:23:28.570 --> 00:23:31.450
We can each have-- so
I cloned all the plants

00:23:31.450 --> 00:23:33.790
and I started
getting into cloning.

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:37.390
I wanted to make a pop-up altar
where people shared stories

00:23:37.390 --> 00:23:38.689
of their mothers with me.

00:23:38.689 --> 00:23:41.230
And in exchange, I would give
them a sprouting plant from one

00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:42.640
of my mom's plants.

00:23:42.640 --> 00:23:45.730
So I wanted to gather and
archive all these stories

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:47.931
and post them up on social
media and on my website

00:23:47.931 --> 00:23:49.930
so that people can listen
to these great stories

00:23:49.930 --> 00:23:53.570
that they told and they shared
about women in their lives.

00:23:53.570 --> 00:23:57.430
So this past Mother's Day,
the day before Mother's Day,

00:23:57.430 --> 00:23:59.920
I was able to set up a little
pop-up on the LA river bed.

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:03.350
And I got a chance to do
it, sit at this huge altar

00:24:03.350 --> 00:24:06.040
of beautiful, green
plants and just

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:08.190
seeing them sort of
perky and happy there--

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:09.690
the plants, that is.

00:24:09.690 --> 00:24:12.160
I was like, this
is for you, Mom.

00:24:12.160 --> 00:24:13.810
And then also,
hearing everyone's

00:24:13.810 --> 00:24:15.820
stories of how
women in their lives

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:19.752
brought so much strength
and the amazing things

00:24:19.752 --> 00:24:20.710
that people remembered.

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:23.740
And also, their connection to
this living thing-- a plant.

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:25.820
What that meant to
a lot of people.

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:28.930
And those stories that I
heard, it was like a constant--

00:24:28.930 --> 00:24:31.890
I felt like that was giving
back because those memories stay

00:24:31.890 --> 00:24:33.390
with people for the
rest of the day.

00:24:33.390 --> 00:24:33.750
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:24:33.750 --> 00:24:35.416
ROSALIE LOPEZ: They
remember that memory

00:24:35.416 --> 00:24:39.002
about grandma or about auntie,
and it stays with them.

00:24:39.002 --> 00:24:40.960
And I thought, man, I
almost forgot about that.

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:42.876
And it was because of
that moment, that event,

00:24:42.876 --> 00:24:44.320
that they got to remember.

00:24:44.320 --> 00:24:46.180
And that's what was
really important for me.

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:49.284
I felt like that
was my anecdote.

00:24:49.284 --> 00:24:50.450
SPEAKER: That was beautiful.

00:24:50.450 --> 00:24:50.900
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Thank you.

00:24:50.900 --> 00:24:51.610
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:52.960
Are you going to do it again?

00:24:52.960 --> 00:24:53.860
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Oh, I'd love to.

00:24:53.860 --> 00:24:56.026
I've always wanted to do
this, like in a flea market

00:24:56.026 --> 00:24:59.650
or swap meet, and have a
different sort of crowd

00:24:59.650 --> 00:25:01.930
and then grow that
archive and just

00:25:01.930 --> 00:25:04.162
continue adding stories
and adding stories to it.

00:25:04.162 --> 00:25:05.620
SPEAKER: Now you
can add all of us.

00:25:05.620 --> 00:25:08.660
We can join you.

00:25:08.660 --> 00:25:10.010
Sandra, you had a story as well.

00:25:10.010 --> 00:25:11.468
SANDRA CORNEJO:
Oh, you could tell?

00:25:11.468 --> 00:25:12.110
SPEAKER: Yes.

00:25:12.110 --> 00:25:14.410
SANDRA CORNEJO: I got one.

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:17.020
So when I recently
moved here-- this

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:19.914
is why I think it's just
like when I moved here,

00:25:19.914 --> 00:25:21.580
all the stars were
just like telling me,

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:24.970
like you're at the right
place at the right time.

00:25:24.970 --> 00:25:29.896
When I had just moved here, I
remember I was in Home Depot,

00:25:29.896 --> 00:25:31.145
and I was like walking around.

00:25:31.145 --> 00:25:33.700
I was like, well, I need
a plant for my new home,

00:25:33.700 --> 00:25:35.350
like, looking around.

00:25:35.350 --> 00:25:38.310
And then I get an
unknown phone call.

00:25:38.310 --> 00:25:41.300
And when I pick up,
Maria [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:41.300 --> 00:25:43.720
is on the other line, at
the other end of the line.

00:25:43.720 --> 00:25:46.360
And I'm not sure if you
guys are familiar with her,

00:25:46.360 --> 00:25:50.120
but she was a very prominent
social justice figure

00:25:50.120 --> 00:25:53.650
here in Los Angeles,
had survived

00:25:53.650 --> 00:25:57.520
through many, many
things in El Salvador

00:25:57.520 --> 00:26:02.320
and resettled in the United
States during the '80s.

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:04.720
So since the '80s,
she's been organizing

00:26:04.720 --> 00:26:06.910
with so many different groups.

00:26:06.910 --> 00:26:08.800
She heard about the
type of work that I

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:14.080
was doing, which is all based
on historical collective memory,

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:17.170
like stories from the
Salvadoran Civil War.

00:26:17.170 --> 00:26:19.870
And she said to me like,
I'd love to meet you.

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:22.450
And you know, I'd
love to talk to you.

00:26:22.450 --> 00:26:26.469
I'd love to have you paint
me, like have a sitting.

00:26:26.469 --> 00:26:27.010
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:29.384
SANDRA CORNEJO: So we talked
about getting that together.

00:26:29.384 --> 00:26:32.320
And I worked with
her for about a year.

00:26:32.320 --> 00:26:34.810
And walked away
from the experience

00:26:34.810 --> 00:26:36.850
with two really
beautiful paintings.

00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:39.010
But throughout that
time span, like

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:41.800
she shared her stories with me.

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:44.110
We would go out for pupusas.

00:26:44.110 --> 00:26:46.840
It's just a lot of
beautiful experiences.

00:26:46.840 --> 00:26:51.610
But she also sat me down
to watch a documentary that

00:26:51.610 --> 00:26:53.140
was done for her.

00:26:53.140 --> 00:26:57.820
So we sat in a room,
held hands sometimes

00:26:57.820 --> 00:27:02.200
because it was just like-- the
story was just really intense.

00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:06.490
But she explained to me, maybe
midway of having spent time

00:27:06.490 --> 00:27:09.070
with her, that she had cancer.

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:10.780
It had come back.

00:27:10.780 --> 00:27:13.730
And she had a certain
amount of time to live.

00:27:13.730 --> 00:27:17.410
So just having the
opportunity to sit with her

00:27:17.410 --> 00:27:20.980
and paint her and
share her story

00:27:20.980 --> 00:27:23.830
and exhibit it in
different spaces

00:27:23.830 --> 00:27:27.160
brought so many people
together from different parts

00:27:27.160 --> 00:27:32.440
of her life that would recognize
that person in the painting.

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:37.930
I walked up to one person,
a patron of mine actually,

00:27:37.930 --> 00:27:41.350
and she was crying when she
was seeing the painting.

00:27:41.350 --> 00:27:45.040
And she shared with me-- like
once Maria had already passed,

00:27:45.040 --> 00:27:47.847
she had shared the stories
that they shared together, like

00:27:47.847 --> 00:27:48.680
through [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:48.680 --> 00:27:53.710
And so I feel like it was just
a very organic and natural thing

00:27:53.710 --> 00:27:55.150
that just happened.

00:27:55.150 --> 00:27:58.120
And I feel fortunate to have
been able to document that

00:27:58.120 --> 00:28:03.219
and to just produce something
that keeps her memory living.

00:28:03.219 --> 00:28:04.510
SPEAKER: That's pretty magical.

00:28:04.510 --> 00:28:05.385
SANDRA CORNEJO: Yeah.

00:28:05.385 --> 00:28:08.050
I'd love to show you
guys the images now.

00:28:08.050 --> 00:28:13.600
But her story was
definitely about survival.

00:28:13.600 --> 00:28:14.600
There's a beauty to it.

00:28:14.600 --> 00:28:17.770
But there was also a
lot of darkness to it.

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:19.839
So I think yeah, it
was just very powerful.

00:28:19.839 --> 00:28:21.130
SPEAKER: Thank you for sharing.

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:22.213
SANDRA CORNEJO: Of course.

00:28:22.213 --> 00:28:24.002
Thank you.

00:28:24.002 --> 00:28:24.710
SPEAKER: Yolanda.

00:28:24.710 --> 00:28:28.710
In all your experience,
tell me one, maybe?

00:28:28.710 --> 00:28:29.370
I don't know.

00:28:29.370 --> 00:28:29.980
Can you?

00:28:29.980 --> 00:28:30.950
Can you reduce it?

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:31.566
I don't know.

00:28:31.566 --> 00:28:33.550
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Yeah,
I could reduce it.

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:35.500
I think one that is very recent.

00:28:35.500 --> 00:28:38.860
I was recently
commissioned by [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:38.860 --> 00:28:44.710
to create a sculpture for
one of their facilities.

00:28:44.710 --> 00:28:50.140
And I have been creating
ceramics for about 20 years.

00:28:50.140 --> 00:28:54.250
And there are these women that I
make that are called [SPANISH]..

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:55.810
And they have these [SPANISH].

00:28:55.810 --> 00:29:00.440
And they're very colorful
and very strong women.

00:29:00.440 --> 00:29:02.500
So they asked me to
create this piece, which

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:05.980
was going to end up being about
six feet tall in ceramics.

00:29:05.980 --> 00:29:07.990
So I started to create it.

00:29:07.990 --> 00:29:11.920
We had the heads that are
large orbs, about this big.

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:15.340
We created the heads,
the torso, and the skirt.

00:29:15.340 --> 00:29:18.160
And it's during a
time where I was

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:23.860
going through a very difficult
transition in my life.

00:29:23.860 --> 00:29:27.640
So we created the skirt,
which is about this tall.

00:29:27.640 --> 00:29:32.170
And it's going into
the kiln and it breaks.

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:34.810
And it was very symbolic of
what I was going through.

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:36.180
We created another one.

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:37.390
It went into the kiln.

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:41.020
When it came out,
it was cracked.

00:29:41.020 --> 00:29:42.550
Then we created a third.

00:29:42.550 --> 00:29:43.810
And when it came out--

00:29:43.810 --> 00:29:47.830
and in some form, I was in
a stronger place and kind

00:29:47.830 --> 00:29:52.090
of more comfortable where
I was and wasn't struggling

00:29:52.090 --> 00:29:53.800
so much with the transition.

00:29:53.800 --> 00:29:54.854
She came out fine.

00:29:54.854 --> 00:29:57.270
SPEAKER: How long was that
process between the first one--

00:29:57.270 --> 00:29:58.895
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
It's been six months.

00:29:58.895 --> 00:30:00.490
It was six months.

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:03.820
And then also, creating the
orbs and the heads for me

00:30:03.820 --> 00:30:05.230
was very organic.

00:30:05.230 --> 00:30:09.490
And feeling these orbs
and creating the portrait,

00:30:09.490 --> 00:30:14.500
I felt it was like, this is what
it would be like to give birth,

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:15.130
this orb.

00:30:15.130 --> 00:30:17.740
I felt it, and it was cool.

00:30:17.740 --> 00:30:22.660
The smell of the clay was
just so beautiful and magical.

00:30:22.660 --> 00:30:23.430
So I created her.

00:30:23.430 --> 00:30:28.480
It took four men to install her
because she's about 600 pounds.

00:30:28.480 --> 00:30:30.970
She was installed.

00:30:30.970 --> 00:30:33.330
And so once she was
installed and I turned around

00:30:33.330 --> 00:30:35.910
and I looked at her, I
cried because I thought,

00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:39.870
we have both completed
this process together.

00:30:39.870 --> 00:30:41.970
And that's what that
piece was for me.

00:30:41.970 --> 00:30:45.420
It was building myself
up again to continue

00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:46.505
what I had to continue.

00:30:46.505 --> 00:30:47.640
SPEAKER: Beautiful.

00:30:47.640 --> 00:30:48.750
Very symbolic.

00:30:48.750 --> 00:30:49.630
Wow.

00:30:49.630 --> 00:30:50.910
So is there anything that--

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:55.100
I know, transitioning
from that is like--

00:30:55.100 --> 00:30:55.600
we cry.

00:30:55.600 --> 00:30:57.516
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: It's
an artist, artist life.

00:30:57.516 --> 00:30:58.820
SPEAKER: Then we get back up.

00:30:58.820 --> 00:31:01.342
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Welcome
to the artist life.

00:31:01.342 --> 00:31:03.300
SPEAKER: So in this roller
coaster of emotions,

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:04.832
is there anything you regret?

00:31:04.832 --> 00:31:05.790
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: None.

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:06.510
SPEAKER: Nothing?

00:31:06.510 --> 00:31:07.593
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Not one.

00:31:07.593 --> 00:31:13.440
SPEAKER: Is there some
type of artwork or genre

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:16.005
that you would never do?

00:31:16.005 --> 00:31:17.280
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Oh, wow.

00:31:17.280 --> 00:31:18.090
SANDRA CORNEJO: Can't
say that, though.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:18.470
SPEAKER: I don't know.

00:31:18.470 --> 00:31:19.011
I don't know.

00:31:19.011 --> 00:31:19.580
I'm asking.

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:20.520
SANDRA CORNEJO: You
can't say never.

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:21.450
We have so much to--

00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:23.033
SPEAKER: Or that you
wouldn't want to.

00:31:23.033 --> 00:31:24.500
Or that you're
like, have fear of.

00:31:24.500 --> 00:31:28.360
Is there like a thing that
you're like, I try to avoid it?

00:31:28.360 --> 00:31:29.860
YOLANDA GONZALEZ:
I think if there's

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:32.440
different mediums, because
people will come to you.

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.300
I was sent to Japan
to do printmaking.

00:31:34.300 --> 00:31:37.810
And I had done some printmaking
at Self Help Graphics, but not

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:39.310
that much.

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:43.890
But what do you do is
you essentially interpret

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:47.831
it, that style, that
medium, in your process.

00:31:47.831 --> 00:31:48.330
SPEAKER: OK.

00:31:48.330 --> 00:31:49.570
So you make it your own?

00:31:49.570 --> 00:31:50.500
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Yes.

00:31:50.500 --> 00:31:52.585
SPEAKER: And then therefore,
it's accepting to you?

00:31:52.585 --> 00:31:52.960
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Yes.

00:31:52.960 --> 00:31:54.032
SPEAKER: But is there
anything else that you

00:31:54.032 --> 00:31:55.390
were like, I don't know?

00:31:55.390 --> 00:31:57.850
I don't want to go there.

00:31:57.850 --> 00:31:59.560
It's not something
that's my style.

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:00.995
I don't want to--

00:32:00.995 --> 00:32:01.495
maybe?

00:32:05.187 --> 00:32:07.020
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It's an
interesting question.

00:32:10.566 --> 00:32:12.180
When I think about
moments in my life

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:14.850
where I wondered if I had
gone this way versus that way,

00:32:14.850 --> 00:32:16.020
I definitely thought about--

00:32:19.240 --> 00:32:22.980
there was a time in my life
when I had just graduated

00:32:22.980 --> 00:32:25.770
and I got my BFA
degree and I was going

00:32:25.770 --> 00:32:28.380
to be going into grad school.

00:32:28.380 --> 00:32:30.390
And there was a
time in between then

00:32:30.390 --> 00:32:34.590
when I lost my
brother unexpectedly

00:32:34.590 --> 00:32:36.280
at a very young age.

00:32:36.280 --> 00:32:37.417
SPEAKER: Sorry.

00:32:37.417 --> 00:32:38.250
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:32:38.250 --> 00:32:39.720
He died of an overdose.

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:41.670
And I was like
really distraught.

00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:44.880
And my family was out of
state, and I was in California.

00:32:44.880 --> 00:32:46.080
I stayed here in California.

00:32:46.080 --> 00:32:47.079
And they had moved away.

00:32:47.079 --> 00:32:49.110
And I really felt like I
wanted to be with them.

00:32:49.110 --> 00:32:52.026
And it was so difficult. But
here I am in a part of my life

00:32:52.026 --> 00:32:54.150
where I'm supposed to decide
where out of state I'm

00:32:54.150 --> 00:32:54.930
going to school.

00:32:54.930 --> 00:32:57.090
And it was a horrible
feeling that should

00:32:57.090 --> 00:32:59.170
have been like much different.

00:32:59.170 --> 00:33:04.530
And so my heart wanted to go to
New Mexico where my family was.

00:33:04.530 --> 00:33:09.930
And I had gotten an opportunity
to go to grad school

00:33:09.930 --> 00:33:11.970
on a Fulbright
Scholarship in Indiana

00:33:11.970 --> 00:33:15.120
University and the thought
of going across the country,

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:16.920
leaving Los Angeles
and going to a place

00:33:16.920 --> 00:33:20.724
where you really are different.

00:33:20.724 --> 00:33:21.930
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:33:21.930 --> 00:33:22.617
Yeah.

00:33:22.617 --> 00:33:24.200
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It
was heart-wrenching.

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:26.550
It was my mom's advice
that sort of pushed me

00:33:26.550 --> 00:33:28.620
into continuing to
go into that route.

00:33:28.620 --> 00:33:32.220
Because it was like, that's what
he would have wanted you to do.

00:33:32.220 --> 00:33:33.640
But it wasn't what
I wanted to do.

00:33:33.640 --> 00:33:35.370
I wanted to go and be with them.

00:33:35.370 --> 00:33:38.610
So I wondered what my life
would be like if I had continued

00:33:38.610 --> 00:33:39.892
and lived out--

00:33:39.892 --> 00:33:41.850
I don't know, maybe
applied to school out there

00:33:41.850 --> 00:33:44.640
and decided to go a
different route with my life.

00:33:44.640 --> 00:33:47.040
But while I was in
Indiana, I totally

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:50.440
got immersed in
using altars as a way

00:33:50.440 --> 00:33:57.675
to remember to heal and to
learn to have my own voice.

00:33:57.675 --> 00:34:01.530
And living in that
place where there's not

00:34:01.530 --> 00:34:04.230
as much social diversity
as we have in Los Angeles,

00:34:04.230 --> 00:34:06.450
it really forced me to
have to talk about my work

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:08.010
to people who didn't
understand it.

00:34:08.010 --> 00:34:08.699
SANDRA CORNEJO: Which is good.

00:34:08.699 --> 00:34:09.280
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:10.446
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It was great.

00:34:10.446 --> 00:34:12.610
Yeah, that experience
was very difficult.

00:34:12.610 --> 00:34:15.520
But also, I think that--

00:34:15.520 --> 00:34:16.020
yeah.

00:34:16.020 --> 00:34:17.860
It just was a point in
my life where I thought,

00:34:17.860 --> 00:34:19.276
I wonder how I
would have ended up

00:34:19.276 --> 00:34:21.225
if I had gone somewhere
else versus here.

00:34:21.225 --> 00:34:22.670
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:34:22.670 --> 00:34:23.692
Wow.

00:34:23.692 --> 00:34:26.159
Yeah.

00:34:26.159 --> 00:34:28.020
Speechless a bit?

00:34:28.020 --> 00:34:29.219
Very strong women.

00:34:29.219 --> 00:34:30.060
Wow.

00:34:30.060 --> 00:34:31.156
I love all these stories.

00:34:31.156 --> 00:34:31.739
And thank you.

00:34:31.739 --> 00:34:33.524
They're very personal.

00:34:33.524 --> 00:34:36.070
We're very thankful that
you're sharing that with us.

00:34:36.070 --> 00:34:37.144
I feel like I'm part of--

00:34:37.144 --> 00:34:38.810
like I'm in your homes
and you're like--

00:34:38.810 --> 00:34:41.010
I need to give you some
[SPANISH] or [SPANISH]..

00:34:41.010 --> 00:34:42.909
SANDRA CORNEJO:
Where's the [SPANISH]??

00:34:42.909 --> 00:34:44.882
SPEAKER: I'm like, this
is really emotional.

00:34:44.882 --> 00:34:49.139
[INAUDIBLE] getting in touch
with these beautiful stories.

00:34:49.139 --> 00:34:49.920
Thank you.

00:34:49.920 --> 00:34:52.070
Wow.

00:34:52.070 --> 00:34:52.639
OK.

00:34:52.639 --> 00:34:56.550
So I want to touch a little
bit more on the whole aspect

00:34:56.550 --> 00:34:59.774
that you were just
touching on of you

00:34:59.774 --> 00:35:02.190
had to explain your art to
people who really didn't get it

00:35:02.190 --> 00:35:03.720
or didn't understand it.

00:35:03.720 --> 00:35:05.010
How was that process?

00:35:05.010 --> 00:35:06.570
Have you had that
experience, too?

00:35:10.887 --> 00:35:12.470
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I'm
going to speak as--

00:35:12.470 --> 00:35:16.710
acknowledging the fact that I'm
very young in this environment.

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:21.710
But it made me realize how much
more I had to study and learn

00:35:21.710 --> 00:35:25.120
the artists who were working
in this form before me.

00:35:25.120 --> 00:35:26.690
And understand
their conversations

00:35:26.690 --> 00:35:29.106
and where it was coming from
because it helped me build up

00:35:29.106 --> 00:35:31.610
my strength to even be able
to communicate these things.

00:35:31.610 --> 00:35:34.610
I want to talk about
a person's life

00:35:34.610 --> 00:35:37.760
and celebrate it without
feeling the drabness of death

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:39.230
and leaving this life.

00:35:39.230 --> 00:35:41.300
And I want to celebrate
them and the lessons

00:35:41.300 --> 00:35:42.385
that they taught me.

00:35:42.385 --> 00:35:43.260
And how do I do that?

00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:46.730
And Dia de los Muertos
and altars and ofrendras

00:35:46.730 --> 00:35:48.800
gave me that venue to be
able to talk about it.

00:35:48.800 --> 00:35:50.840
So I studied.

00:35:50.840 --> 00:35:51.830
I researched.

00:35:51.830 --> 00:35:56.210
I definitely wanted
to investigate

00:35:56.210 --> 00:36:00.080
a lot of Chicanas who were
using altars as another way.

00:36:00.080 --> 00:36:02.300
Not just to commemorate
their [INAUDIBLE],,

00:36:02.300 --> 00:36:05.090
but as a way to talk about
the social dynamics of where

00:36:05.090 --> 00:36:06.420
they're coming from.

00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:10.645
And how they can communicate
that in a public atmosphere.

00:36:10.645 --> 00:36:13.640
It doesn't have to be
in a whitewall gallery.

00:36:13.640 --> 00:36:15.840
It can be in a public space.

00:36:15.840 --> 00:36:20.451
So growing up in LA, and having
places like Self Help Graphics

00:36:20.451 --> 00:36:22.909
that are pioneering contemporary
Dia de los Muertos, de los

00:36:22.909 --> 00:36:25.410
Muertos, the Chicanoized
version of Dia de los Muertos,

00:36:25.410 --> 00:36:28.240
it was like setting
the pathway for me

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:31.160
to discuss all of
these things and to be

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:33.770
who I wanted to be and
talk about my family

00:36:33.770 --> 00:36:37.640
and also my situation and relate
it to everyone else around me.

00:36:37.640 --> 00:36:41.150
And even though I was
all the way in Indiana,

00:36:41.150 --> 00:36:44.350
I had the access to resources
to do this homework,

00:36:44.350 --> 00:36:48.900
to look at books and
to read and research.

00:36:48.900 --> 00:36:51.590
So when I came back home, I
felt like a lot more empowered

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:53.510
to understand it when
you kind of take it

00:36:53.510 --> 00:36:55.460
for granted a little
bit growing up in it.

00:36:55.460 --> 00:36:57.057
SPEAKER: Sure.

00:36:57.057 --> 00:36:57.890
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:36:57.890 --> 00:36:58.340
SPEAKER: That's great.

00:36:58.340 --> 00:36:59.965
And you empowered a
ton of other people

00:36:59.965 --> 00:37:01.265
and now they're more educated.

00:37:01.265 --> 00:37:03.787
You empowered everyone here.

00:37:03.787 --> 00:37:04.620
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:37:04.620 --> 00:37:06.680
It's more than just like
[SPANISH] and makeup.

00:37:06.680 --> 00:37:08.630
And you know, let's
not forget this--

00:37:08.630 --> 00:37:10.130
SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE]
pretty picture.

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:11.310
Exactly.

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:12.350
Of course.

00:37:12.350 --> 00:37:13.940
Thank you.

00:37:13.940 --> 00:37:15.566
Sandra, you were
going to say anything?

00:37:15.566 --> 00:37:16.065
No?

00:37:16.065 --> 00:37:16.640
Maybe?

00:37:16.640 --> 00:37:17.891
But I do have a question.

00:37:17.891 --> 00:37:18.390
Tell me.

00:37:18.390 --> 00:37:22.220
So we were discussing this
voice that you have as artists.

00:37:22.220 --> 00:37:25.670
How has social media, or
digital, or technology

00:37:25.670 --> 00:37:28.650
helped your careers?

00:37:28.650 --> 00:37:30.560
Or not?

00:37:30.560 --> 00:37:31.937
Maybe not.

00:37:31.937 --> 00:37:33.520
SANDRA CORNEJO: Well,
I mean, it helps

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:36.130
in the sense of
having you connected

00:37:36.130 --> 00:37:38.340
with so many of your
peers and your colleagues.

00:37:38.340 --> 00:37:41.650
And I mean, being
able to research.

00:37:41.650 --> 00:37:48.010
And especially the way that
I gather source material.

00:37:48.010 --> 00:37:52.000
I very much needed the
internet and social media

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:53.140
to be able to do that.

00:37:56.122 --> 00:37:58.430
But in particular, maybe.

00:37:58.430 --> 00:37:59.122
I don't know.

00:37:59.122 --> 00:38:00.267
Maybe not.

00:38:00.267 --> 00:38:00.850
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:04.990
I'm very intrigued by
the fact that art is now

00:38:04.990 --> 00:38:06.670
accessible to all.

00:38:06.670 --> 00:38:08.740
So the minute you
do something, it

00:38:08.740 --> 00:38:11.530
is seen by millions and
millions of eyeballs

00:38:11.530 --> 00:38:13.990
all over the world instantly.

00:38:13.990 --> 00:38:16.660
And so when you're making this
now, because it's different.

00:38:16.660 --> 00:38:18.250
Maybe even 30 years ago, right?

00:38:18.250 --> 00:38:19.390
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: Oh, yeah.

00:38:19.390 --> 00:38:20.990
SPEAKER: I mean, when you're
creating something now--

00:38:20.990 --> 00:38:22.448
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I
want to hear hers.

00:38:22.448 --> 00:38:25.090
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I was
excited about beepers.

00:38:25.090 --> 00:38:26.380
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Page me.

00:38:26.380 --> 00:38:28.660
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: How can
I make love with a beeper?

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:29.780
Turn it around.

00:38:29.780 --> 00:38:30.573
It's not 8-3-8-3.

00:38:30.573 --> 00:38:31.726
It's love.

00:38:31.726 --> 00:38:32.850
SPEAKER: It's 1-4-3, 1-4-3.

00:38:32.850 --> 00:38:33.990
I was there, too.

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:36.520
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I remember
the phones with the long cords.

00:38:36.520 --> 00:38:38.104
Yeah.

00:38:38.104 --> 00:38:40.270
SPEAKER: So Yolanda, I have
a question for you then.

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:42.280
So in the 30-year
span, you've gone

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:44.390
from you didn't have
digital, really,

00:38:44.390 --> 00:38:46.510
to now having people
see your artwork,

00:38:46.510 --> 00:38:49.254
if they wanted to,
around the world.

00:38:49.254 --> 00:38:50.920
Does it change now
your perspective when

00:38:50.920 --> 00:38:53.660
you're painting in the
sense that before, people

00:38:53.660 --> 00:38:55.870
would go and--

00:38:55.870 --> 00:38:58.299
wherever you had the
exhibition, people would see it.

00:38:58.299 --> 00:38:59.590
It was that [INAUDIBLE] people.

00:38:59.590 --> 00:39:00.460
Maybe you toured.

00:39:00.460 --> 00:39:02.890
Whatever it is, those are
the people who saw it, right?

00:39:02.890 --> 00:39:04.240
Who seeked it out.

00:39:04.240 --> 00:39:06.160
But now anybody can
see it and share it.

00:39:06.160 --> 00:39:09.100
Does that change
how you paint now

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:13.264
and the voice or the
message you want to give?

00:39:13.264 --> 00:39:15.430
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I think
it changes a lot of things

00:39:15.430 --> 00:39:17.140
except for the way I paint.

00:39:17.140 --> 00:39:20.050
Because the painting
process and my relationship

00:39:20.050 --> 00:39:23.590
with the creative process
is very pure to me.

00:39:23.590 --> 00:39:25.060
It's very sacred.

00:39:25.060 --> 00:39:29.140
And so that is very strong one
of the strongest relationships

00:39:29.140 --> 00:39:30.910
I have.

00:39:30.910 --> 00:39:36.100
But it's very exciting
to me to share.

00:39:36.100 --> 00:39:39.940
And what I like to
do is put a piece--

00:39:39.940 --> 00:39:42.760
when I first start the
sketch, the rough, when

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:44.980
it's almost done, and
then when it's completed.

00:39:44.980 --> 00:39:47.350
So people can kind
of see the process

00:39:47.350 --> 00:39:51.880
of what's happening
of creation, so be it.

00:39:51.880 --> 00:39:55.300
People put their kid's pictures
every month on Facebook.

00:39:55.300 --> 00:39:58.105
And I put my paintings
every month on Facebook.

00:39:58.105 --> 00:39:59.431
Those are my babies.

00:39:59.431 --> 00:39:59.930
That's it.

00:39:59.930 --> 00:40:01.110
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I think that's
what's exciting about it,

00:40:01.110 --> 00:40:04.180
is like we get to see the
studio practice unfurled

00:40:04.180 --> 00:40:06.145
in front of us on
Instagram and Facebook.

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:11.320
And it's also hard to get used
to it, to opening people up

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:12.055
to that process.

00:40:12.055 --> 00:40:13.930
SANDRA CORNEJO: How much
do you want to show?

00:40:13.930 --> 00:40:15.940
How much is exposed?

00:40:15.940 --> 00:40:18.357
Like you want to keep some of
those things private, right?

00:40:18.357 --> 00:40:20.689
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: It's whatever
you're comfortable with.

00:40:20.689 --> 00:40:22.750
It's whatever you're
comfortable really sharing.

00:40:22.750 --> 00:40:23.800
Because it's out there.

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:25.720
And once it's out
there, it's out there.

00:40:25.720 --> 00:40:27.880
But it is amazing.

00:40:27.880 --> 00:40:33.070
And I've utilized it
to the fullest where

00:40:33.070 --> 00:40:34.960
you send out your message.

00:40:34.960 --> 00:40:36.340
And you send out your images.

00:40:36.340 --> 00:40:37.900
And then, you
represent messages that

00:40:37.900 --> 00:40:40.750
need to be represented as well.

00:40:40.750 --> 00:40:47.354
But I think it's a fascinating
process, the internet.

00:40:47.354 --> 00:40:48.520
It's just fascinating to me.

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:52.180
And I'm such a gadget person.

00:40:52.180 --> 00:40:53.470
I love that.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:58.690
So anything I can get my little
hands on and expose people

00:40:58.690 --> 00:41:01.570
to what's going on, or my
world, my little utopian,

00:41:01.570 --> 00:41:03.570
strange world, it's there.

00:41:03.570 --> 00:41:04.780
SPEAKER: That's great.

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:06.982
ROSALIE LOPEZ: It's exciting.

00:41:06.982 --> 00:41:08.440
I feel like we're
living in a world

00:41:08.440 --> 00:41:10.565
where there's all kinds of
new technology happening

00:41:10.565 --> 00:41:11.560
all the time.

00:41:11.560 --> 00:41:13.900
And as artists, we
get to figure out how

00:41:13.900 --> 00:41:15.470
to interpret that and use that.

00:41:18.430 --> 00:41:19.720
I'm a printmaker.

00:41:19.720 --> 00:41:21.659
And it's one of those
classic dying forms

00:41:21.659 --> 00:41:23.200
that people don't
like to use anymore

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:24.850
because it's very cumbersome.

00:41:24.850 --> 00:41:26.830
But there's always
this conversation

00:41:26.830 --> 00:41:28.990
on how we're pulling
from new technology

00:41:28.990 --> 00:41:30.490
to influence our work.

00:41:30.490 --> 00:41:33.340
So how do we keep it
relevant in this age

00:41:33.340 --> 00:41:38.170
of like constant
technology upgrades?

00:41:38.170 --> 00:41:41.500
I'd like to see how it impacts
the conversation I want to have

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:45.520
or the way I envision
a piece happening.

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:48.170
Some of the ways that I've used
it is I'm a graphic designer.

00:41:48.170 --> 00:41:50.710
So a lot of the work also
starts off on the computer

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:54.340
and using digital programs or
digitizing the work somehow.

00:41:54.340 --> 00:41:57.290
And then, seeing how
the work can transmute.

00:41:57.290 --> 00:42:00.490
I've had a chance to use CNC
router machines to create

00:42:00.490 --> 00:42:03.990
custom furniture pieces that are
reminiscent of my papel picado

00:42:03.990 --> 00:42:04.490
patterns.

00:42:04.490 --> 00:42:06.300
And that was an
amazing experience

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:07.759
or like laser-cutting
machines that

00:42:07.759 --> 00:42:09.758
take papel picado [INAUDIBLE]
whole other world.

00:42:09.758 --> 00:42:11.590
What happens when the
machine cuts it out?

00:42:11.590 --> 00:42:14.980
And you have these little burned
edges and how those things

00:42:14.980 --> 00:42:16.630
start to impact the message.

00:42:16.630 --> 00:42:21.520
And I'd be excited to be able
to play with it even more.

00:42:21.520 --> 00:42:25.180
I think what becomes a biggest
deterrent is accessibility.

00:42:25.180 --> 00:42:26.120
It's expensive.

00:42:26.120 --> 00:42:28.760
It's hard to get access to.

00:42:28.760 --> 00:42:31.400
Especially once you're outside
and you don't have access

00:42:31.400 --> 00:42:33.530
to a university or
anything like that,

00:42:33.530 --> 00:42:39.380
how do you use this
equipment in your work?

00:42:39.380 --> 00:42:42.680
Yeah, I'd be excited to try
to learn to use it more.

00:42:42.680 --> 00:42:47.190
And it provides
another way for you

00:42:47.190 --> 00:42:50.040
to have that communication
so any other way that I

00:42:50.040 --> 00:42:52.530
can try to use technology.

00:42:52.530 --> 00:42:54.360
I've used it for
sharing the stories

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:56.460
that I'm collecting to
have this online archive

00:42:56.460 --> 00:42:59.250
or an online altar.

00:42:59.250 --> 00:43:02.280
So I try to use it
as much as possible,

00:43:02.280 --> 00:43:06.720
but I think that there's
also some deterrence because

00:43:06.720 --> 00:43:08.409
of the accessibility of it, too.

00:43:08.409 --> 00:43:09.200
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:10.110
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:12.110
SPEAKER: They're big machines
you're talking about, too.

00:43:12.110 --> 00:43:12.740
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:43:12.740 --> 00:43:14.430
I'm interested in how
they collide, though.

00:43:14.430 --> 00:43:16.110
How do you think the old
school and the classic

00:43:16.110 --> 00:43:17.410
with like the new technology?

00:43:17.410 --> 00:43:19.520
SPEAKER: And there's the
3D printers now, too.

00:43:19.520 --> 00:43:20.895
ROSALIE LOPEZ:
Yeah, 3D printing.

00:43:20.895 --> 00:43:23.231
I'd love to mess around
with that kind of machinery.

00:43:23.231 --> 00:43:23.730
Yeah.

