SPEAKER: Nice.

00:43:24.810 --> 00:43:27.400
Well, so now I'm going to open
it up to the audience as well.

00:43:27.400 --> 00:43:29.940
If you have any
questions at all, please,

00:43:29.940 --> 00:43:31.449
this is your time to--

00:43:31.449 --> 00:43:33.240
SANDRA CORNEJO: There's
the microphone box.

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:33.300
SPEAKER: See?

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:34.210
The one we were talking about.

00:43:34.210 --> 00:43:35.418
The one you can throw around.

00:43:35.418 --> 00:43:37.600
ROSALIE LOPEZ: A Google Cube.

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:40.185
SPEAKER: Anybody have questions?

00:43:40.185 --> 00:43:41.670
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:43:41.670 --> 00:43:42.660
[INAUDIBLE]

00:43:47.620 --> 00:43:48.454
Hi, everyone.

00:43:48.454 --> 00:43:49.120
My name is Eric.

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:51.540
So first of all, thank you
guys for spending an afternoon

00:43:51.540 --> 00:43:51.930
with us.

00:43:51.930 --> 00:43:54.305
I thought this was really
interesting and really awesome.

00:43:54.305 --> 00:43:56.910
And I'm really happy
that you guys came by.

00:43:56.910 --> 00:43:59.440
So now, my question
is, a few months ago,

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:04.350
there was like a case in Canada,
where a writer was criticized

00:44:04.350 --> 00:44:07.410
for saying that other writers
and artists should take

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:10.200
and write from the point of
view of different ethnicities,

00:44:10.200 --> 00:44:11.912
cultures, genders,
and background.

00:44:11.912 --> 00:44:14.370
And so I was kind of curious
to hear what you guys thought,

00:44:14.370 --> 00:44:18.844
if you would encourage others to
sort of take the point of view

00:44:18.844 --> 00:44:20.760
of people that come from
different backgrounds

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:21.301
that they do?

00:44:23.670 --> 00:44:25.920
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I think
that's a big responsibility.

00:44:25.920 --> 00:44:26.795
SPEAKER: It is, yeah.

00:44:26.795 --> 00:44:28.590
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I
only have my own view.

00:44:28.590 --> 00:44:34.200
And I can't expect everybody
to respect or accept

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:38.950
my point of view on a whole
of a culture, an ethnicity.

00:44:38.950 --> 00:44:40.107
I don't think that's right.

00:44:40.107 --> 00:44:41.940
SANDRA CORNEJO: I think
any artist out there

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:43.890
that's making work--

00:44:43.890 --> 00:44:45.780
I mean, their true
aspiration should

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:51.130
be to convey a truly honest
perspective of their own.

00:44:51.130 --> 00:44:53.652
So I feel like being
able to share that.

00:44:53.652 --> 00:44:55.110
I mean, that's how
other people are

00:44:55.110 --> 00:44:57.570
able to learn about it, right?

00:44:57.570 --> 00:45:01.110
But to put yourself
in a different place?

00:45:01.110 --> 00:45:02.010
It gets tricky.

00:45:02.010 --> 00:45:02.880
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:45:02.880 --> 00:45:03.390
ROSALIE LOPEZ: You
don't want to be

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:06.340
put in a position where you're
the spokesperson for everyone.

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:07.770
And that just doesn't seem fair.

00:45:07.770 --> 00:45:11.340
It's important to be
inclusive, to be aware.

00:45:11.340 --> 00:45:15.480
But to be put in
the position of I'm

00:45:15.480 --> 00:45:18.060
the spokesperson for
Latinas, and I would never

00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:19.700
want that responsibility.

00:45:19.700 --> 00:45:22.590
There's too many voices
out there to be heard.

00:45:22.590 --> 00:45:27.120
So yeah, that's a
pretty tough criticism.

00:45:27.120 --> 00:45:27.757
Yeah.

00:45:27.757 --> 00:45:29.340
SPEAKER: It's also
a lot of hard work.

00:45:29.340 --> 00:45:30.548
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Good question.

00:45:30.548 --> 00:45:31.830
Yeah.

00:45:31.830 --> 00:45:32.590
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:32.980
AUDIENCE: Definitely.

00:45:32.980 --> 00:45:34.080
And I completely agree.

00:45:34.080 --> 00:45:38.630
Like I mean, there's the variety
of opinions about it, I guess.

00:45:38.630 --> 00:45:42.170
And like on one side,
you should say like, oh,

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:44.375
by encouraging people to
talk about cultures that

00:45:44.375 --> 00:45:45.750
are different than
their own, you

00:45:45.750 --> 00:45:48.750
encourage them to
find commonalities,

00:45:48.750 --> 00:45:51.429
to find ways to empathize.

00:45:51.429 --> 00:45:53.970
And then from the other point
of view, kind of like you said,

00:45:53.970 --> 00:45:56.130
it's, well, there
are many people that

00:45:56.130 --> 00:45:58.020
could talk about this
particular experience,

00:45:58.020 --> 00:46:01.470
so why is somebody that may
not have as much experience

00:46:01.470 --> 00:46:04.680
or knowledge in that background
take it upon themselves

00:46:04.680 --> 00:46:05.909
to talk about it?

00:46:05.909 --> 00:46:08.200
So I was kind of curious to
hear what you guys thought.

00:46:08.200 --> 00:46:09.240
So thank you.

00:46:09.240 --> 00:46:10.990
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Thank
you for the question.

00:46:13.791 --> 00:46:14.540
AUDIENCE: So cool.

00:46:16.932 --> 00:46:18.640
Ladies, thank you so
much for being here.

00:46:18.640 --> 00:46:22.330
And I want to take it to
the business perspective.

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:28.480
Women traditionally make
$0.72 of the dollar of males.

00:46:28.480 --> 00:46:33.010
Black women make $0.62
and Latinas even less.

00:46:33.010 --> 00:46:35.800
So I'm wondering, in terms
of your male counterparts

00:46:35.800 --> 00:46:39.160
as artists when you're
comparing art to art, do

00:46:39.160 --> 00:46:41.530
you find yourself having to--

00:46:41.530 --> 00:46:46.137
or not making as much as
men do in the industry?

00:46:46.137 --> 00:46:48.220
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Do we choose
to price it less than,

00:46:48.220 --> 00:46:48.440
is that what you're saying?

00:46:48.440 --> 00:46:48.981
AUDIENCE: No.

00:46:48.981 --> 00:46:51.480
Are people wanting you to
charge less because you're

00:46:51.480 --> 00:46:54.590
women or Latinas?

00:46:54.590 --> 00:46:55.771
SPEAKER: That's interesting.

00:46:59.449 --> 00:47:01.240
SANDRA CORNEJO: I've
seen that on both ends

00:47:01.240 --> 00:47:04.279
of the different artists
I've worked with since being

00:47:04.279 --> 00:47:04.945
in Los Angeles--

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:12.040
the more recognized, like male
figure, and a woman that's

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:15.190
been struggling and
really putting in the work

00:47:15.190 --> 00:47:18.550
since she began,
like decades ago.

00:47:18.550 --> 00:47:23.200
And just realizing
that there's that--

00:47:23.200 --> 00:47:28.690
like women tend to
under-price their work.

00:47:28.690 --> 00:47:31.060
I don't know.

00:47:31.060 --> 00:47:34.200
It's difficult.

00:47:34.200 --> 00:47:37.230
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I
think as a woman artist,

00:47:37.230 --> 00:47:42.480
it's important not to
under-price my work,

00:47:42.480 --> 00:47:47.480
to value my work for the years
that I've been creating art.

00:47:47.480 --> 00:47:51.270
And it's been 30 long years.

00:47:51.270 --> 00:47:56.640
And I think it's a huge
responsibility for the artists,

00:47:56.640 --> 00:47:58.800
the young artists,
who are following

00:47:58.800 --> 00:48:02.640
me to open the door for them
not only through my art,

00:48:02.640 --> 00:48:04.300
but through my business sense.

00:48:04.300 --> 00:48:08.399
So you educate people to pay if
they want a piece of your art.

00:48:08.399 --> 00:48:09.690
They want a piece of your soul.

00:48:09.690 --> 00:48:12.599
They're paying for it properly.

00:48:12.599 --> 00:48:14.890
SANDRA CORNEJO: And if they
don't buy it at that price,

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:15.800
then they don't deserve it.

00:48:15.800 --> 00:48:17.883
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: If they
don't buy at that price,

00:48:17.883 --> 00:48:19.690
somebody else will.

00:48:19.690 --> 00:48:21.250
And I have little pieces.

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:23.080
You can get a little
piece about this big.

00:48:23.080 --> 00:48:23.920
You can take home.

00:48:23.920 --> 00:48:25.077
That will be fine.

00:48:25.077 --> 00:48:26.542
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:48:26.542 --> 00:48:28.750
SANDRA CORNEJO: Yeah, you
just got to know your worth

00:48:28.750 --> 00:48:29.807
and stick to it.

00:48:29.807 --> 00:48:32.140
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: And it's
hard because a lot of artists

00:48:32.140 --> 00:48:35.100
are not businesspeople.

00:48:35.100 --> 00:48:38.230
I think it's
difficult to separate

00:48:38.230 --> 00:48:42.070
because you're emotionally
involved to this piece of art.

00:48:42.070 --> 00:48:44.260
But then what you do
is you find somebody

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:50.910
who you trust to represent your
art and to market it that way.

00:48:50.910 --> 00:48:51.680
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:48:51.680 --> 00:48:52.910
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:48:52.910 --> 00:48:57.320
I struggle with that a
lot as well because I

00:48:57.320 --> 00:48:59.210
worry about accessibility.

00:48:59.210 --> 00:49:04.370
And I think that when
those things are true,

00:49:04.370 --> 00:49:06.590
pricing and the
time and what you've

00:49:06.590 --> 00:49:09.830
invested, where your career
is at, all of those things

00:49:09.830 --> 00:49:11.630
that factor into pricing.

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:13.460
And then, some of the
things I worry about

00:49:13.460 --> 00:49:15.860
is like, who can buy that?

00:49:15.860 --> 00:49:17.450
Who is going to be
able to buy that?

00:49:17.450 --> 00:49:19.430
Who am I making it for?

00:49:19.430 --> 00:49:22.370
And even though I
know it's not going

00:49:22.370 --> 00:49:24.830
to make me very much
money, I want my artwork

00:49:24.830 --> 00:49:25.770
to be accessible.

00:49:25.770 --> 00:49:28.520
I don't want it to be
unreachable, unattainable for

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:30.260
people to be able to purchase.

00:49:30.260 --> 00:49:32.330
So I need to hire
a businessperson.

00:49:32.330 --> 00:49:36.200
[LAUGHS] I feel like I
want a little of both.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:38.727
I think that creating
tiers of work

00:49:38.727 --> 00:49:40.310
that you can sell
for different prices

00:49:40.310 --> 00:49:43.040
helps to make things
that are accessible.

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:46.040
And you have bigger ideas.

00:49:46.040 --> 00:49:49.640
A lot of my work is
installation artwork, too.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:51.180
I don't really intend on--

00:49:51.180 --> 00:49:52.730
it's a temporary installation.

00:49:52.730 --> 00:49:54.420
And it exists for
that point in time.

00:49:54.420 --> 00:49:57.790
So sales, a lot of times,
aren't really the driving force.

00:49:57.790 --> 00:50:00.650
It's more like, how can
I complete this idea?

00:50:00.650 --> 00:50:02.960
I just moved back to Los
Angeles after living away

00:50:02.960 --> 00:50:03.680
for six years.

00:50:03.680 --> 00:50:06.560
And this past year
that I've been back,

00:50:06.560 --> 00:50:08.115
I've really been
forced to think--

00:50:08.115 --> 00:50:10.490
the people and the friends
that I've met have really made

00:50:10.490 --> 00:50:12.200
me think a lot about pricing.

00:50:12.200 --> 00:50:16.430
And I was sort of living in, I
feel like, my own little dream

00:50:16.430 --> 00:50:18.800
world of I just want
to do the idea, man.

00:50:18.800 --> 00:50:20.990
I'm just trying to get
this idea out there.

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:23.180
The cash wasn't even about it.

00:50:23.180 --> 00:50:25.070
And that's kind of
the struggling part,

00:50:25.070 --> 00:50:27.987
so that's why I teach.

00:50:27.987 --> 00:50:29.570
That's one of the
reasons why I teach.

00:50:29.570 --> 00:50:30.361
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:50:30.361 --> 00:50:32.570
SANDRA CORNEJO: Got
to have that side job.

00:50:32.570 --> 00:50:34.340
ROSALIE LOPEZ: So I
can have that freeness

00:50:34.340 --> 00:50:36.560
to be able to create what
I want to create and not

00:50:36.560 --> 00:50:37.690
be driven by the price.

00:50:37.690 --> 00:50:40.460
But it's a struggling
game of back and forth.

00:50:40.460 --> 00:50:42.710
And you know, Yolanda's
very established

00:50:42.710 --> 00:50:45.950
and has a lot of years.

00:50:45.950 --> 00:50:49.280
And I hope one day to
kind of get to a level

00:50:49.280 --> 00:50:55.190
where I can be a lot more
demanding with it, too.

00:50:55.190 --> 00:50:59.630
But I also think there's
a line, too, about where

00:50:59.630 --> 00:51:02.330
you want to be open and
have people find you and get

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:06.170
to know you and create that
relationship through being

00:51:06.170 --> 00:51:08.670
a little more accessible.

00:51:08.670 --> 00:51:10.487
Yeah, it's difficult.
It's very difficult.

00:51:10.487 --> 00:51:12.570
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I think
as far as accessibility,

00:51:12.570 --> 00:51:14.270
if somebody comes
into the studio

00:51:14.270 --> 00:51:19.460
and they really want a piece,
instead of lowering the price,

00:51:19.460 --> 00:51:21.590
if it's a small
piece or something,

00:51:21.590 --> 00:51:23.850
I'll just give it to them.

00:51:23.850 --> 00:51:25.405
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I
got payment plans.

00:51:25.405 --> 00:51:26.324
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: No.

00:51:26.324 --> 00:51:27.240
I literally just say--

00:51:27.240 --> 00:51:28.380
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Layaway.

00:51:28.380 --> 00:51:30.540
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I
just say, take it.

00:51:30.540 --> 00:51:31.810
If you want it, take it.

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:37.190
I have a watercolor series
that's really, really

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:39.020
reasonable for my work.

00:51:39.020 --> 00:51:41.480
But some of the paintings now--

00:51:41.480 --> 00:51:44.795
when I was your guys age, I
would paint five, six, seven,

00:51:44.795 --> 00:51:46.970
10 paintings in a week.

00:51:46.970 --> 00:51:47.470
Now--

00:51:47.470 --> 00:51:50.100
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Pump it out.

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:53.670
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: That's
why I have shoulder pain.

00:51:53.670 --> 00:51:56.710
But now, it's once a month.

00:51:56.710 --> 00:51:59.360
It's It slows down.

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:02.410
But that's just where I'm at.

00:52:02.410 --> 00:52:05.372
That's just what 30 years
of the process has taken me.

00:52:05.372 --> 00:52:06.830
And I have to be
accepting of that.

00:52:06.830 --> 00:52:10.130
I'm not 25 anymore.

00:52:10.130 --> 00:52:14.610
But anytime you want to come
over and talk, we'll talk.

00:52:14.610 --> 00:52:15.110
I'm there.

00:52:15.110 --> 00:52:16.148
I'm open to that.

00:52:20.630 --> 00:52:21.938
SPEAKER: Any other questions?

00:52:24.930 --> 00:52:27.420
So I'm going to end with
one last one since--

00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:28.350
any other questions?

00:52:32.120 --> 00:52:35.250
Back to the next
generation, I love--

00:52:35.250 --> 00:52:40.270
there's a ton of people who
not only are digital natives.

00:52:40.270 --> 00:52:43.220
They don't know anything
else but the online world

00:52:43.220 --> 00:52:45.800
but also are really
intrigued or really want

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:48.845
to explore art as part
of who they are, maybe

00:52:48.845 --> 00:52:50.930
as their career.

00:52:50.930 --> 00:52:54.230
What advice can you give
them, for this next generation

00:52:54.230 --> 00:52:55.700
of artists?

00:52:55.700 --> 00:52:58.210
I always believe that you
can't just have technology.

00:52:58.210 --> 00:52:59.210
You can't just have art.

00:52:59.210 --> 00:53:02.840
I think the combination
works really nicely now,

00:53:02.840 --> 00:53:07.040
especially now with STEAM,
where you can do both.

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:10.250
What advice can you give the
next generation of people

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:12.320
or kids who want to pursue art?

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:18.770
YOLANDA GONZALEZ: I think
just the old classic,

00:53:18.770 --> 00:53:20.060
follow your dream.

00:53:20.060 --> 00:53:25.430
But now, the dream is very large
and vast with the internet.

00:53:25.430 --> 00:53:27.560
And I think it's
amazing for them

00:53:27.560 --> 00:53:31.160
to have that accessibility
to the internet.

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:34.760
But I also think that the
classic way of learning art

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:36.210
is very important.

00:53:36.210 --> 00:53:38.720
So I think if there
is a way to have

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:42.770
the classic way of learning
art, which is pencil, charcoal,

00:53:42.770 --> 00:53:49.460
still life and then transfer
that into the internet,

00:53:49.460 --> 00:53:52.670
and combine it, and incorporate
it, and collaborate with it.

00:53:52.670 --> 00:53:55.793
I think that's the fascinating
part of the new art we're going

00:53:55.793 --> 00:54:00.190
to be seeing in the future.

00:54:00.190 --> 00:54:01.522
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:54:01.522 --> 00:54:03.230
SANDRA CORNEJO: Know
where you come from.

00:54:03.230 --> 00:54:06.710
Continue to be curious,
explore, and just

00:54:06.710 --> 00:54:10.280
continue to ask questions,
like within your own work.

00:54:10.280 --> 00:54:11.247
Definitely.

00:54:11.247 --> 00:54:11.830
SPEAKER: Nice.

00:54:15.374 --> 00:54:16.540
ROSALIE LOPEZ: I don't know.

00:54:16.540 --> 00:54:20.440
I have thought about this
question a few different ways.

00:54:20.440 --> 00:54:23.610
There's a lot of artists now who
solely exist on social media,

00:54:23.610 --> 00:54:27.060
like their main venues
are on social media.

00:54:27.060 --> 00:54:30.520
And they have a really hard
time doing the classic stuff.

00:54:30.520 --> 00:54:31.260
[INAUDIBLE]

00:54:31.260 --> 00:54:33.330
Like, I already got
this many followers

00:54:33.330 --> 00:54:34.955
and they're all--
you know what I mean?

00:54:34.955 --> 00:54:36.746
It's a different
way of thinking.

00:54:36.746 --> 00:54:38.370
But I think that's
the challenge of how

00:54:38.370 --> 00:54:43.290
the classic and traditional
still engage that newer age,

00:54:43.290 --> 00:54:44.909
because they found
ways to bypass

00:54:44.909 --> 00:54:46.200
a lot of the traditional stuff.

00:54:46.200 --> 00:54:50.010
Why do I need to learn how
to draw the figure if I'm

00:54:50.010 --> 00:54:55.530
doing specific performances
in random spots in LA

00:54:55.530 --> 00:54:57.630
and I'm getting commissions?

00:54:57.630 --> 00:54:59.430
And they're getting
paid for doing it.

00:54:59.430 --> 00:55:01.020
So it's the challenge
that I think

00:55:01.020 --> 00:55:02.910
that the institution
hasn't quite yet led up

00:55:02.910 --> 00:55:06.120
to learning how to teach
those students how to keep up

00:55:06.120 --> 00:55:08.520
with it all, because they're
struggling with keeping up

00:55:08.520 --> 00:55:11.740
with that new technology.

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:14.350
I think, too, that
I remember being

00:55:14.350 --> 00:55:20.110
a student and the mode of
thinking being like, concept,

00:55:20.110 --> 00:55:21.250
concept, concept.

00:55:21.250 --> 00:55:23.870
And those things
are really amazing.

00:55:23.870 --> 00:55:27.422
If you're wanting
to be an artist,

00:55:27.422 --> 00:55:28.880
there's different
types of artists.

00:55:28.880 --> 00:55:30.730
Some people just paint
in their basements

00:55:30.730 --> 00:55:32.350
and never expose
it to the public.

00:55:32.350 --> 00:55:34.414
It's about that moment
that they're creating.

00:55:34.414 --> 00:55:36.580
And it's not really about
sharing it with everybody.

00:55:36.580 --> 00:55:37.990
Some other people
have the yearning

00:55:37.990 --> 00:55:39.573
to want to share it
out in the public.

00:55:39.573 --> 00:55:41.530
And it's about that
communication, the way

00:55:41.530 --> 00:55:44.170
that people perceive
it in a public space.

00:55:44.170 --> 00:55:46.060
And that's what
drives that force.

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:48.700
So I don't know that I would
have one piece of advice

00:55:48.700 --> 00:55:49.210
for artists.

00:55:49.210 --> 00:55:55.330
It would be like, what's
your main goal for this?

00:55:55.330 --> 00:55:58.210
Yeah, it's like STEM is
huge right now in schools.

00:55:58.210 --> 00:56:00.670
And you hear-- like I'm
looking for jobs all the time

00:56:00.670 --> 00:56:03.700
and they want to know how
you can incorporate STEM

00:56:03.700 --> 00:56:06.080
into your curriculum.

00:56:06.080 --> 00:56:08.020
And I think that
acceleratingly, it's

00:56:08.020 --> 00:56:10.390
more important because the
schools have stripped away

00:56:10.390 --> 00:56:12.850
like a lot of those arts and
creatives out of the school,

00:56:12.850 --> 00:56:14.890
but they want to
bring it on again

00:56:14.890 --> 00:56:19.120
as an educational component
to teach them science,

00:56:19.120 --> 00:56:20.950
to teach them all
these other things.

00:56:20.950 --> 00:56:23.532
But where can art
exist just for art?

00:56:23.532 --> 00:56:25.990
When you're a kid, you think
you're thinking about concept?

00:56:25.990 --> 00:56:26.489
No.

00:56:26.489 --> 00:56:28.150
You're remembering
that fun part of why

00:56:28.150 --> 00:56:30.730
you want to make art,
of what it is to create.

00:56:30.730 --> 00:56:32.230
And it's important
not to lose that.

00:56:32.230 --> 00:56:34.600
We're so strained, I think,
to have this a greater,

00:56:34.600 --> 00:56:36.070
bigger social message.

00:56:36.070 --> 00:56:37.880
And those things
are very important,

00:56:37.880 --> 00:56:41.260
but there should also still
live a space where you can just

00:56:41.260 --> 00:56:42.645
be free to create just because.

00:56:42.645 --> 00:56:45.790
And you may not
know why, but you

00:56:45.790 --> 00:56:47.800
need to have that
happen at the same time

00:56:47.800 --> 00:56:50.530
that other people are more
driven by that message.

00:56:50.530 --> 00:56:53.170
So to have both
existing simultaneously,

00:56:53.170 --> 00:56:54.572
I think and not
knock people down

00:56:54.572 --> 00:56:56.530
for having a different
way of thinking about it

00:56:56.530 --> 00:56:59.064
or working with it.

00:56:59.064 --> 00:56:59.980
SPEAKER: That's great.

00:56:59.980 --> 00:57:01.546
I agree completely.

00:57:01.546 --> 00:57:02.920
I think there's
a space for both.

00:57:02.920 --> 00:57:04.260
And also, separately.

00:57:04.260 --> 00:57:04.570
ROSALIE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:57:04.570 --> 00:57:05.486
SPEAKER: And together.

00:57:05.486 --> 00:57:07.270
Why not, right?

